Amnesty International South Africa says the state is failing South Africans and migrants by not dealing with crime and allowing impunity to continue around xenophobic attacks. The organisation adds that authorities need to step up and deal with these xenophobic attacks on vulnerable migrants who have become scapegoats for communities unhappy with the levels of crime. RELATED: Anti-foreign operations such as Dudula are serious threat to rule of law - ISS Mandy Wiener chats to Amnesty International South Africa  executive director Shenilla Mohamed to give more insight on the matter. A 2019 reported we released found that the asylum system in South Africa is broken and this has resulted in people living in limbo.  People who have genuinely escaped conflicts are being grouped with economic migrants and are all being treated the same way, she says. When you find someone without the right papers, it is probably because the asylum system at Home Affairs is not doing what it is supposed to do.  Listen below to the full conversation:  This article first appeared on 702 : Asylum system in SA is broken and is failing migrants - Amnesty International